        <li>Needham, J., "China’s Trebuchets, Manned and Counterweighted," in B.S. Hall and D.C. West (eds) <em>On Pre-Modern Technology and Science: Studies in Honour</em> of Lynn White, Jr., Malibu, Ca Udena, 1976.</li> 
        <li>Nicolle, David, <em>Warriors and their Weapons around the Time of the Crusades</em>. Relationships Between Byzantium, the West and the Islamic World, Ashgate, 2002.</li> 
        <li>Norman, A.V.B. and Pottinger, Don, <em>English Weapons and Warfare 449-1660</em>, 1979.</li> 
        <li>Despite its title it provides an excellent general introduction.</li> 
        <li>Oakeshott, R. Ewart, <em>The Sword in the Age of Chivalry</em>, 1981.</li> 
        <li>The best study of the knight's principal weapon.</li> 
        <li>Patterson, W.F.A., <em>A Guide to the Crossbow</em> (ed. A.G. Credland) Burnham Society of Archer Antiquaries, 1990.</li> 
        <li>Pierce, I., "The Knight, His Arms and Armour in the Eleventh and Twelfth Centuries," in C. Harper-Bill and R. Harvey (eds). <em>Ideals and Practice of Medieval Knighthood</em>, Woodbridge: Boydell, 1986, pp. 152-64.</li> 
        <li>Pierce, I., "Arms and Armour in Warfare in the Eleventh Century," <em>Battle</em> 10 (1987), pp. 237-57.</li> 
        <li>Sawyer, P. and Hilton, R. "Technical Determinism, the Stirrup, and the Plough," <em>Past and Present</em> 24 (1963), pp. 90-100.</li> 
        <li>White, Lynn, <em>Medieval Technology and Social Change</em>, 1962.</li> 
       </ul> 
